</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3E0655AFFC3FFADFA7B1ECFF5E1F43F" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8B4536D1FFC3FFADFA7B1ECFF5E1F43F" blockId="4.[1430,2641,1855,3070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis id="B98EEAC3FFC3FFADFA7B1ECFF932F500" bold="true" box="[1432,1776,2760,2793]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
CITES Appendix II. Classified as Data Deficient on The IUCN Red List. There are no estimates of global population size of Shepherd’s Beaked Whale. [tis rarely sighted at sea and may be naturally rare within its distribution. Like other species of beaked whales,it is potentially affected by ingestion of plastic debris and noise pollution, and it may be caught as bycatch in driftnet fisheries. As a species that is apparently restricted to cooler waters, it may also be vulnerable to effects of climate change. Nevertheless, nothing is known about the form or extent of these potential impacts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3E0655AFFC3FFADFA7A1FEEF79CF417" box="[1433,2142,3049,3070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="349" type="bibRefCitation_list">
